{
  "doc_id": "5202",
  "text": "It is becoming increasingly evident that populations of genetically identical cells of the same type maintained under identical conditions exhibit heterogeneous transcriptomes, and thus may have previously unappreciated heterogeneous functions and/or fates [CITATION_1] . This cellular heterogeneity appears to be common among varied processes dictating cell fate, including cell cycle/mitosis [CITATION_2] , apoptosis [CITATION_3] , and developmental potential of stem cells [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The foundational population of the adult male germ line-SSCs-emerges early in postnatal development from a subset of undifferentiated spermatogonia. Mounting evidence suggests that SSCs are remarkably heterogeneous on the phenotypic level [5-10, 12, 17, 19-21] . Yet, the origin and extent of phenotypic heterogeneity among undifferentiated spermatogonia have remained poorly understood. The advent of high-throughput single-cell gene expression technology has allowed us to begin to address this knowledge gap by performing a series of gene expression studies using single-cell qRT-PCR to examine mRNA abundance for a panel of genes in individual P6 testis cells and to identify substantial heterogeneity among undifferentiated spermatogonia.",
